description like that.

00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:28.279
But in order to be able to do so, well, hang on, there's a problem.

00:05:28.279 --> 00:05:31.480
We've seen warnings like this out there on Twitter and from other resources, and in particular

00:05:31.480 --> 00:05:35.239
from this book, which I want to point out is if you read one book this year, read this

00:05:35.239 --> 00:05:36.239
one.

00:05:36.239 --> 00:05:40.239
Even if you're not seeking a job, it's called Build a Career in Data Science from Emily

00:05:40.239 --> 00:05:42.000
Robinson and Jacqueline Nollis.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:46.519
I devoured it in like three days, and they very eloquently kind of map out the challenge

00:05:46.519 --> 00:05:50.559
here, where they say there are lots of listings that look like the previous one that I just

00:05:50.559 --> 00:05:53.559
described, but it might be a red flag that the company doesn't know what they actually

00:05:53.559 --> 00:05:59.559
want from a data scientist, and so you might want to sort of beware, and yet I just claim

00:05:59.559 --> 00:06:03.760
that these unicorns are real, and importantly that we should pay them the right amount.

00:06:03.760 --> 00:06:07.399
So back to the exercise, how do we do this?

00:06:07.399 --> 00:06:11.399
To do this, you'll notice I had a co-author on this talk, her name is Donna Evans, she's

00:06:11.399 --> 00:06:16.920
a senior compensation consultant at Moffitt, and to know how the job description moves

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:22.399
from those words to a quantitative salary estimate for the person that you want to hire,

00:06:22.399 --> 00:06:26.000
I needed to understand the black box voodoo that happens in the middle, so she helped

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.239
me with that, and here it goes.

00:06:28.239 --> 00:06:31.600
So the hiring manager writes a job description, we all knew that was coming first, I think,

00:06:31.600 --> 00:06:35.519
you actually only have to write a couple of things in that job description, the first

00:06:35.519 --> 00:06:40.200
being the primary purpose and the expected deliverables, there's almost a one liner,

00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:45.119
why does this job exist in this company, right, you just got to say that, and then some requirements

00:06:45.119 --> 00:06:48.920
around technical skills, prior experience, and or education, and these don't have to

00:06:48.920 --> 00:06:51.760
be extremely verbose.

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:55.320
With that information, HR will then classify the role, they'll give it a title, in this

00:06:55.320 --> 00:06:59.440
case we're going to be working with the data science title, data scientist, and within

00:06:59.440 --> 00:07:02.480
that domain they'll classify whether or not this is going to be an hourly or a salary

00:07:02.480 --> 00:07:07.480
role, so exempt versus non-exempt, the type of contributor, are they a technician, a professional

00:07:07.480 --> 00:07:12.040
or a scientist, and within each of those domains, what level are they contributing at, so entry

00:07:12.040 --> 00:07:15.239
through principal.

00:07:15.239 --> 00:07:18.959
Once they have that classification in hand, they turn to benchmarking data, which is purchased

00:07:18.959 --> 00:07:25.679
from compensation survey companies, and those data resources are a bit different than what

00:07:25.679 --> 00:07:30.279
you might be used to, so if like me you've sat down and Googled what does a data scientist

00:07:30.279 --> 00:07:35.119
at company ABC make, you'll get some results back, and it'll probably be self-reported

00:07:35.119 --> 00:07:39.480
results from someone who said I worked at company ABC a couple of years ago and I made

00:07:39.480 --> 00:07:40.480
this.

00:07:40.480 --> 00:07:43.880
And that's valid, but there are problems with that sort of data, self-report bias, it's

00:07:43.880 --> 00:07:47.839
incomplete, other things like that, so it might not be the best.

00:07:47.839 --> 00:07:49.799
These compensation survey companies are pretty different.

00:07:49.799 --> 00:07:54.359
What they do is they have clients who purchase the data from them, and as part of that agreement,

00:07:54.359 --> 00:07:58.839
they contribute data back, so the organization that has bought the data then goes across

00:07:58.839 --> 00:08:02.359
their organization and they say here are all the job descriptions and the job titles that

00:08:02.359 --> 00:08:06.880
we have, and here's what those people actually make today, and so then they send those back

00:08:06.880 --> 00:08:09.279
to the compensation survey company and they aggregate it and they send it back out to

00:08:09.279 --> 00:08:10.920
all their clients, right?

00:08:10.920 --> 00:08:16.480
So importantly, these are now salaries that are real-time, more or less, from warm bodies

00:08:16.480 --> 00:08:19.359
in those positions, and that's important.

00:08:19.359 --> 00:08:25.239
Then HR divisions usually purchase more than one such survey, so at Moffitt we have many,

00:08:25.239 --> 00:08:29.239
and we sort of just, the HR, our HR group will take them and aggregate them together,

00:08:29.239 --> 00:08:32.760
maybe summarize them, take a median and an intercore trial range, and then according

00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:37.559
to any individual organization's compensation philosophy, that's how you come at the number.

00:08:37.559 --> 00:08:40.960
So the compensation philosophy could vary a little bit, for example, in the startup

00:08:40.960 --> 00:08:46.719
world where things like bonus incentives, stock options, all that stuff is more common,

00:08:46.719 --> 00:08:50.000
the base salary might dip a little bit lower because you have all those other things, and

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.840
of course there are companies on the other end of that spectrum, but that's sort of where,

00:08:52.840 --> 00:08:56.320
that's how this happens, more or less.

00:08:56.320 --> 00:09:02.099
So I iterated with Donna a couple times to understand how I could write a job description

00:09:02.099 --> 00:09:07.400
that mapped to roles that appear in those compensation surveys.

00:09:07.400 --> 00:09:10.039
So for title, the data scientist title was obvious.

00:09:10.039 --> 00:09:13.039
We started there, and that ended up being a pretty good decision.

00:09:13.039 --> 00:09:16.919
And then within these surveys, they tend to have five levels for data scientists, so one

00:09:16.919 --> 00:09:20.640
being entry level, and then five being a principal data scientist, kind of at the senior end

00:09:20.640 --> 00:09:22.219
of these things.

00:09:22.219 --> 00:09:25.280
So here, we'll walk through them, here's a data scientist one.

00:09:25.280 --> 00:09:28.880
Generically, they're going to do the thing that all data scientists do, right?

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:32.840
Summarize and analyze potentially complex and large data to guide business insights.

00:09:32.840 --> 00:09:35.979
That's just what probably most of you do.

00:09:35.979 --> 00:09:39.700
And then they'll do some other stuff that we would expect, merge and tidy data, do some

00:09:39.700 --> 00:09:45.179
visualizations, organize databases, maybe do some analysis, they'll produce reports,

00:09:45.179 --> 00:09:47.619
and they'll make it accessible to the end users.

00:09:47.619 --> 00:09:51.059
I have a bullet in there which is where I just wrote kind of RStack experience just

00:09:51.059 --> 00:09:56.619
off the top of my head, and this is incomplete even for me, but I importantly put a wild

00:09:56.619 --> 00:09:59.419
card here for you if you're writing job descriptions.

00:09:59.419 --> 00:10:04.739
You can put in whatever R stuff that you would like your person to know in there, and it

00:10:04.739 --> 00:10:08.700
will not change the leveling of these things, to my knowledge.

00:10:08.700 --> 00:10:11.179
I checked that with Don, and that seems to be true.

00:10:11.179 --> 00:10:15.299
The last two are actually the important bullet points when it comes to salary benchmarking.

00:10:15.299 --> 00:10:16.940
May require an advanced degree.

00:10:16.940 --> 00:10:22.179
So May is HR code speak for not required, so we don't actually need that in this role.

00:10:22.179 --> 00:10:26.500
And zero to two years of related experience preferred, also preferred being code speak

00:10:26.500 --> 00:10:28.099
for not required.

00:10:28.099 --> 00:10:33.020
So this is very much aligning with an entry-level position, and that's good.

00:10:33.020 --> 00:10:37.539
And so the notes are things that do not appear actually in the job posting, but it's important

00:10:37.539 --> 00:10:41.020
for you to know, to think about how this data scientist will operate.

00:10:41.020 --> 00:10:45.179
This one will report to manager and have their work closely managed, because they're entry-level,

00:10:45.179 --> 00:10:49.419
and their projects often have limited complexity as they kind of learn the nuance of the role.

00:10:49.419 --> 00:10:53.979
I'll move to two, and you'll see that nothing changes except that last bullet point.

00:10:53.979 --> 00:10:57.979
So I left the purpose and the RStack, all that stuff the same, and now we just have

00:10:57.979 --> 00:11:02.979
two to four years of related experience, typically required, so they need some kind of experience,

00:11:02.979 --> 00:11:06.539
but here's where you can start to mix and match experience with advanced degrees.

00:11:06.539 --> 00:11:09.659
So if someone has an advanced degree in some quantitative science or computer science or

00:11:09.659 --> 00:11:13.419
whatever it may be, you can swap that out for the two to four years of related experience,

00:11:13.419 --> 00:11:15.719
and you'll get a data scientist, too.

00:11:15.719 --> 00:11:18.619
And now they're requiring occasional direction, so you don't need someone looking over their

00:11:18.619 --> 00:11:23.340
shoulder all the time, and they're getting some exposure to complex tasks of the job.

00:11:23.340 --> 00:11:27.700
Three, now we have four to seven years of experience, or an appropriate mix of that

00:11:27.700 --> 00:11:31.619
and an advanced degree, right, so if they have an advanced degree, this counts as two

00:11:31.619 --> 00:11:35.900
to five years of experience, depending on what sort of degree we're talking about.

00:11:35.900 --> 00:11:40.219
And now they require minimal direction, so more autonomy as we move through these stages,

00:11:40.219 --> 00:11:41.580
more complex challenges.

00:11:41.580 --> 00:11:42.580
Here's a four.

00:11:42.580 --> 00:11:47.719
This work is primarily independent from this contributor, and they often lead teams for

00:11:47.719 --> 00:11:50.099
complex problems.

00:11:50.099 --> 00:11:53.020
Seven plus years of related experience, again, may be an appropriate mix with an advanced

00:11:53.020 --> 00:11:57.859
degree, and lastly we have the principal data scientist, data scientist five, who is fully

00:11:57.859 --> 00:12:02.260
autonomous and they're leading their teams to tackle the most challenging problems encountered

00:12:02.260 --> 00:12:03.820
by the data science unit.

00:12:03.820 --> 00:12:04.820
So that's it.

00:12:04.820 --> 00:12:05.820
That's one through five.

00:12:05.820 --> 00:12:06.820
These are the job descriptions.

