00:14:15.659 --> 00:14:17.099
So talk to them.

00:14:17.099 --> 00:14:19.020
That will help.

00:14:19.020 --> 00:14:22.059
This is something important that I took home from this.

00:14:22.059 --> 00:14:24.940
Primary drivers of salary estimates are experience.

00:14:24.940 --> 00:14:28.979
This is like years of experience and autonomy of the role.

00:14:28.979 --> 00:14:32.619
And it's not like the number of languages that you know.

00:14:32.619 --> 00:14:34.260
I think there's a temptation among all of us.

00:14:34.260 --> 00:14:35.260
Certainly it's true for me.

00:14:35.260 --> 00:14:37.700
I'm always like, well, if I just knew that one more language or that one, like if I took

00:14:37.700 --> 00:14:41.099
this bootcamp or whatever, my career trajectory would look different.

00:14:41.099 --> 00:14:43.840
I don't think that's necessarily true.

00:14:43.840 --> 00:14:47.659
Particularly for our users, you know a lot and you can deliver a lot of value to any

00:14:47.659 --> 00:14:49.979
institution that you choose to join.

00:14:49.979 --> 00:14:53.380
Feel empowered to apply for those roles and you should get them because I think you're

00:14:53.380 --> 00:14:54.380
all awesome.

00:14:54.380 --> 00:14:56.979
So you don't need like language X.

00:14:56.979 --> 00:15:01.340
You just probably need R, at least in my opinion.

00:15:01.340 --> 00:15:04.739
And these drivers, unfortunately, I don't know that they're totally correct, right,

00:15:04.739 --> 00:15:06.539
for data science in particular.

00:15:06.539 --> 00:15:07.940
Autonomy, fair enough.

00:15:07.940 --> 00:15:11.340
But experience, it's hard to have ten plus years experience in a technology which isn't

00:15:11.340 --> 00:15:13.340
ten or more years old.

00:15:13.340 --> 00:15:17.099
Like Shiny is a semi-arbitrary example, right?

00:15:17.099 --> 00:15:20.140
I don't really know how to navigate that and there's not really good solutions in the

00:15:20.140 --> 00:15:22.460
HR domain, but I think at least they're aware of it.

00:15:22.460 --> 00:15:27.700
So at individual organizations, you can talk to them about that sort of thing.

00:15:27.700 --> 00:15:31.719
The salary surveys are not yet capturing specific data science roles.

00:15:31.719 --> 00:15:35.299
So again, in the build a data science career book, they do a very great job of spelling

00:15:35.299 --> 00:15:37.219
out all the data science subdomains.

00:15:37.219 --> 00:15:41.940
So like machine learning engineer, a decision scientist, all kinds of business intelligence

00:15:41.940 --> 00:15:42.940
analysts, all this stuff.

00:15:42.940 --> 00:15:44.780
There's all these words.

00:15:44.780 --> 00:15:46.820
And they do a good job of spelling that out.

00:15:46.820 --> 00:15:51.419
Because that hasn't been standardized for a long period of time, many companies aren't

00:15:51.419 --> 00:15:54.140
hiring into those titles and so they're not reporting out data on those.

00:15:54.140 --> 00:16:00.260
So we do not yet have data on how much each of those sub-niche roles sort of make.

00:16:00.260 --> 00:16:03.020
But that will change in the coming years.

00:16:03.020 --> 00:16:05.219
I'm not arguing for or against the current process.

00:16:05.219 --> 00:16:07.020
I'm just telling you what it is.

00:16:07.020 --> 00:16:10.900
I'm kind of powerless against the machine, just like so many of us are, right?

00:16:10.900 --> 00:16:14.739
I mean, there are federal laws that are in play here.

00:16:14.739 --> 00:16:20.900
So you really can't diverge too much from what the standards actually are.

00:16:20.900 --> 00:16:25.000
But at least by understanding the process, you may be empowered to understand if you're

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:29.380
a job seeker, where you land in the data science one through five track.

00:16:29.380 --> 00:16:32.580
And if you're a manager, it might also empower you to help know how you want to write the

00:16:32.580 --> 00:16:35.380
job description to get the unicorn that you actually need.

00:16:35.380 --> 00:16:39.099
I feel a thank here.

00:16:39.099 --> 00:16:44.140
So Don Evans, of course, my compensation consultant and HR guru, she was immensely helpful.

00:16:44.140 --> 00:16:47.900
Jordan Creed, many of you probably already saw her because she was giving out the unicorn

00:16:47.900 --> 00:16:49.940
hex stickers, which she also made.

00:16:49.940 --> 00:16:55.500
She's a great data scientist and apparently also a future PR representative.

00:16:55.500 --> 00:17:00.380
Gary Caden-Booey, I've seen him thanked in at least half the talks here.

00:17:00.380 --> 00:17:05.020
And he's similar here because he makes so many good tools that everybody uses.

00:17:05.020 --> 00:17:07.060
I benefit from working with him.

00:17:07.060 --> 00:17:10.420
I was able to get advanced access to the share engine extra package, which made a lot of

00:17:10.420 --> 00:17:14.819
the fanciness that you saw in these slides happen if you're interested in such things.

00:17:14.819 --> 00:17:19.540
This ggiraffe, I think is how it's called, package, is what made that interactive map

00:17:19.540 --> 00:17:23.180
happen within the slides outside the context of Plotly.

00:17:23.180 --> 00:17:26.819
Also if you're interested in how those things work, that's a pretty great package.

00:17:26.819 --> 00:17:28.579
Thanks to the Tampa user group.

00:17:28.579 --> 00:17:30.380
They did quick feedback on this.

00:17:30.380 --> 00:17:33.859
I gave a little preview of this talk a few weeks ago, and they gave some great feedback.

00:17:33.859 --> 00:17:36.500
Again, Emily and Jacqueline for that book.

00:17:36.500 --> 00:17:37.500
There's a link.

00:17:37.500 --> 00:17:38.500
Please do check it out.

00:17:38.500 --> 00:17:40.699
If you're interested in any of these sorts of topics, you'll find that book fascinating.

00:17:40.699 --> 00:17:43.900
They're going to the resources, that's how you find me on Twitter.

00:17:43.900 --> 00:17:44.900
Thank you again.

00:17:44.900 --> 00:17:47.900
It's so awesome to be here.

00:17:47.900 --> 00:17:55.500
Thank you so much, Travis.

00:17:55.500 --> 00:17:58.660
We have a few questions that are queued up for you.

00:17:58.660 --> 00:18:04.020
The first one is, there are still many job descriptions that specify Python only, and

00:18:04.020 --> 00:18:07.540
sometimes they even say R is insufficient.

00:18:07.540 --> 00:18:11.780
How should our community approach this situation?

00:18:11.780 --> 00:18:12.780
That can be valid.

00:18:12.780 --> 00:18:17.339
If an institution has a large technology stack that's built around Python, there's probably

00:18:17.339 --> 00:18:19.420
not much of a way to get around it.

00:18:19.420 --> 00:18:22.540
You can go in there and do a lot of the same things with R, but in particular if it's a

00:18:22.540 --> 00:18:26.380
large organization, you're not going to be able to knock down the Python vertical and

00:18:26.380 --> 00:18:29.300
put up R in its place as a new employee.

00:18:29.300 --> 00:18:31.219
I disagree strongly with the R is insufficient.

00:18:31.219 --> 00:18:32.219
I don't know.

00:18:32.219 --> 00:18:35.699
You probably don't want to work at that place.

00:18:35.699 --> 00:18:36.699
Let's just say it.

00:18:36.699 --> 00:18:37.699
All right.

00:18:37.699 --> 00:18:38.699
Yeah.

00:18:38.699 --> 00:18:39.699
Fair enough.

00:18:39.699 --> 00:18:44.300
Next question was actually about how the map was built, which you answered on your last

00:18:44.300 --> 00:18:45.300
slide.

00:18:45.300 --> 00:18:46.300
Oh, great.

00:18:46.300 --> 00:18:50.900
Next one is, how can data scientists develop their autonomy?

00:18:50.900 --> 00:18:57.500
What should we read, learn, and do?

00:18:57.500 --> 00:19:00.579
I suppose demonstrating that you have independent packages.

00:19:00.579 --> 00:19:01.619
Everybody looks for the portfolio.

00:19:01.619 --> 00:19:04.099
Every hiring manager says, oh, do you have a GitHub?

00:19:04.099 --> 00:19:05.540
Most these days do, right?

00:19:05.540 --> 00:19:08.060
What's your GitHub portfolio look like?

00:19:08.060 --> 00:19:11.760
And I also appreciate the fact that it's a lot to ask people on their free time to build

00:19:11.760 --> 00:19:14.540
up their own projects because they're often currently working with a company where things

00:19:14.540 --> 00:19:17.020
are protected and they can't share them openly.

00:19:17.020 --> 00:19:18.260
I don't know what a good solution for that is.

00:19:18.260 --> 00:19:20.819
A lot of people are talking about that, but that probably is the best way, honestly.

00:19:20.819 --> 00:19:25.660
As someone who looks at CVs and resumes, I can usually get a good sense of how autonomous

00:19:25.660 --> 00:19:31.500
they are by looking at their repository, set of repositories.

00:19:31.500 --> 00:19:32.859
One more question.

00:19:32.859 --> 00:19:40.180
What are the federal regulations that hamstring HR into these processes that you criticized?

00:19:40.180 --> 00:19:41.660
So what is it?

00:19:41.660 --> 00:19:43.380
The Fair Standards and Labor Act?

00:19:43.380 --> 00:19:44.380
Are there any HR people?

00:19:44.380 --> 00:19:45.380
Yeah.

00:19:45.380 --> 00:19:46.380
I'm seeing nodding heads.

00:19:46.380 --> 00:19:48.219
I know Jeff Leak alluded to this yesterday in his talk in the morning, unfortunately,

00:19:48.219 --> 00:19:49.579
but I heard it was awesome.

00:19:49.579 --> 00:19:53.739
So he's facing the same things whereby he is training people who don't have advanced

00:19:53.739 --> 00:19:59.859
degrees through data science, and he wants to hire them into advanced data science roles.

00:19:59.859 --> 00:20:05.140
But often that particular law says that those people cannot be salaried because they fall

00:20:05.140 --> 00:20:06.819
in between a couple of different categories.

00:20:06.819 --> 00:20:10.660
So Jeff is really a go-to on that, but that is one of the nuances that makes this really

00:20:10.660 --> 00:20:11.660
hard.

00:20:11.660 --> 00:20:12.660
Yeah.

00:20:12.660 --> 00:20:13.660
Yeah.

00:20:13.660 --> 00:20:14.660
Makes sense.

00:20:14.660 --> 00:20:22.020
How does this correlate with the number of heck stickers on my laptop?

00:20:22.020 --> 00:20:25.900
I can give Donna some numbers, and then I can report back.

00:20:25.900 --> 00:20:26.900
I'll fix the math.

00:20:26.900 --> 00:20:32.219
Or do a pull request if anybody wants to do that, and we can do it that way.

00:20:32.219 --> 00:20:38.260
A lot of jobs are requiring data scientist skills, but calling it a data analyst position.

00:20:38.260 --> 00:20:39.260
How do you differ the two?

00:20:39.260 --> 00:20:40.260
Yeah.

00:20:40.260 --> 00:20:43.060
So, I mean, you're going to have to try to read between the lines in those job descriptions.

00:20:43.060 --> 00:20:45.780
Data analyst is a different thing than a data scientist.

00:20:45.780 --> 00:20:50.300
I think, at least in the Build a Data Science Career book, they specify an analyst to be

00:20:50.300 --> 00:20:52.099
a bit a tier below the data scientist.

00:20:52.099 --> 00:20:54.099
They're not aggregating as much data.

00:20:54.099 --> 00:20:57.099
They're typically closely managed and things like that.

00:20:57.099 --> 00:21:01.260
But there are other organizations that, for historical reasons, have a data analyst role,

00:21:01.260 --> 00:21:04.099
which performs all the tasks of a full-blown data scientist.

00:21:04.099 --> 00:21:07.859
And when they benchmark the salaries of the data analyst against these survey companies,

00:21:07.859 --> 00:21:11.140
they'll actually use the data scientist title, even though that's not what they're being

00:21:11.140 --> 00:21:12.140
called in the company.

00:21:12.219 --> 00:21:13.739
So, it's tricky.

00:21:13.739 --> 00:21:16.739
Just read the description, and maybe, if you go on an interview, try to tease out what

00:21:16.739 --> 00:21:17.739
it is they're actually having you do.

00:21:17.739 --> 00:21:21.939
I'm going to read off one more question, Ben Joaquim, if you don't mind starting to set

00:21:21.939 --> 00:21:22.939
up.

00:21:22.939 --> 00:21:23.939
That would be great.

00:21:23.939 --> 00:21:30.020
So, public universities, they often have rigid, capped salary scales.

00:21:30.020 --> 00:21:34.619
Our unicorns are golden...

00:21:34.619 --> 00:21:35.619
Our unicorns are golden.

00:21:35.619 --> 00:21:36.619
Full stop.

00:21:36.619 --> 00:21:42.099
It's a golden-hooved data scientist who value working in academia.

00:21:42.099 --> 00:21:43.619
Tips for those job ads?

00:21:43.619 --> 00:21:46.780
I mean, academia is tricky.

00:21:46.780 --> 00:21:51.140
There's another layer of federal requirements around those things that are related to federal

00:21:51.140 --> 00:21:54.420
grant money.

00:21:54.420 --> 00:21:58.619
If you spelled out in a budget that you're going to pay a data analyst or something like

00:21:58.619 --> 00:22:02.020
that, X amount of dollars, you're kind of bound within the context of that grant to

00:22:02.020 --> 00:22:03.020
pay them that.

00:22:03.020 --> 00:22:07.739
Although, many faculty or investigators will have additional kinds of streams of money

00:22:07.739 --> 00:22:09.140
that they may have access to.

00:22:09.140 --> 00:22:13.300
So, feel empowered to seek the salary that you know you're worth.

00:22:13.300 --> 00:22:14.780
That's my parting words.

00:22:14.780 --> 00:22:16.300
Travis, thank you so much.

00:22:16.300 --> 00:22:17.300
Thank you.

00:22:17.300 --> 00:22:17.300


